\section{Conclusions}
\label{sec:conclude}


In this {paper} we have {revisited and updated the constraints} on the parameter space of {the real scalar singlet extension of} the SM. In comparison with the previous results presented in Ref.~\cite{Robens:2015gla}, {the most important improvements have been made in the constraints from new results in LHC searches for a heavy Higgs boson decaying into vector boson final states, as well as from the ATLAS and CMS combination of the signal strength of the discovered Higgs state.} We found that these modify our previous findings in the mass range $130\,{\ensuremath\rm GeV} \leq m_H\,\leq\,250\,{\ensuremath\rm GeV}$, where now the direct Higgs searches as well as the {ATLAS and CMS} signal strength combination render the {strongest} constraints on the parameter space. 

Based on these updated results, we have {provided} benchmark {scenarios} for {both the high mass and low mass region for upcoming LHC searches.} {Hereby, we pursued the philosophy of selecting those points which feature a maximal discovery potential in a dedicated collider search of the corresponding signature.} We provided predictions of production cross sections {for} the LHC at 14 {\ensuremath\rm TeV}{, and supplemented these with information about the branching fractions of the relevant decay modes}. 
We {encourage} the {experimental collaborations} to {make use} of the{se} benchmark {scenarios in} the current {and upcoming} LHC run{s}.

